table-1511-336.caption: Tramping
data: Passing the former Armed Constabulary Redoubt near the start of the trail, the track then climbs steeply up onto Panekire Bluff. The bluffs form part of the southern shore, and provide spectacular views over the expanse of the lake. Following the ridge, the trail has several sharp dips and climbs. Panekire Hut sits in a small clearing next to the Panekire Trig point (1180m), at the top of the cliffline, with excellent views of the lake.

Passing the former Armed Constabulary Redoubt near the start of the trail, the track then climbs steeply up onto Panekire Bluff. The bluffs form part of the southern shore, and provide spectacular views over the expanse of the lake. Following the ridge, the trail has several sharp dips and climbs. Panekire Hut sits in a small clearing next to the Panekire Trig point (1180m), at the top of the cliffline, with excellent views of the lake.

The trail from Panekire Hut goes west, climbing and descending over the Panekire Range, before eventually descending precipitously into much taller and wetter forest. At the end of the descent lies Waiopaoa Hut and Campsite, on the edge of the Waiopaoa Inlet part of the lake.

The trail from Panekire Hut goes west, climbing and descending over the Panekire Range, before eventually descending precipitously into much taller and wetter forest. At the end of the descent lies Waiopaoa Hut and Campsite, on the edge of the Waiopaoa Inlet part of the lake.
This section has a very large number of meanders in the trail, as it follows the lakeside, and toward the Maraunui Campsite, follows a river upstream, before crossing it, and returning downstream.
This section has a very large number of meanders in the trail, as it follows the lakeside, and toward the Maraunui Campsite, follows a river upstream, before crossing it, and returning downstream.
A brief walk through grassland and over a small ridge.
A brief walk through grassland and over a small ridge.
Apart from a brief climb over a small peninsula, the trail follows the shoreline as it meanders northeast.
Apart from a brief climb over a small peninsula, the trail follows the shoreline as it meanders northeast.

Climbing fairly steeply, the trail crosses the neck of the Puketukutuku Peninsula, touching the edge of the Kiwi Reserve area. Descending the other side of the peninsula, the trail arrives at the Tapuaenui Campsite, back on the lake shore.

Again following the shore, the trail meanders along, through forest, before arriving at Whanganui Hut.

After a short walk through the forest, the trail arrives at the beach where water taxis pickup and set-down passengers (they use the rocks on the east end of the beach). Sandflies are a problem whilst waiting here.

table-1511-292.caption: April 10 event
data: Homes were unroofed and barns were destroyed.
Tornado damaged roofs, telephone poles, trees, and overturned a truck, but remained over open country while at peak intensity. Tornado was well documented on film and by NSSL storm researchers.
Second, much weaker tornado in the area.
Large tornado destroyed several barns and scattered debris over a large area.
Homes and barns were ripped apart.
Barns were destroyed and homes sustained roof damage. A woman was injured when her truck rolled into the ditch in which she was taking cover.
Three houses were destroyed and several others were damaged.
A mobile home was destroyed in the Faxson area, resulting in two serious injuries. Other homes in the are were damaged. Tornado left suction vortex marks in open fields.
3 deaths - Strong tornado struck Lawton, destroying over 116 structures, and damaging over 330 others. One of the fatalities occurred when a car was tossed from a road.
Two trailers were destroyed, and three homes were damaged. One person was injured.
Severe damage in the Pruitt City area. 44 homes and mobile homes were damaged or destroyed. Several vehicles, including a bus, were flipped and tossed.

table-1511-293.caption: April 11 event
data: A trailer and three barns were destroyed.
Six barns and two homes were destroyed. Other homes, barns, and outbuildings were damaged.
Three homes were destroyed and others were damaged.
Several buildings were torn apart and a cemetery was damaged. Caused $190,000 in damage.
Several trailers were destroyed. Damage also occurred to machinery, homes and outbuildings.
Caused over $300,000 in damage to homes, barns, and a rock crushing plant.
Homes and businesses were torn apart in the McGehee area. Caused a total of $449,000 in damage.

A concrete block building was destroyed, and another was partially destroyed. A home was badly damaged, losing a large portion of its front side. Two barns were also destroyed and scattered across a field.

Several homes and businesses, a mobile home park, a church, and a school were damaged. Three barns were destroyed as well. 5 bus passengers were injured when they took shelter in a ditch, only to have the bus roll onto them.
